An orally bioavailable protein-protein interaction (PPI) inhibitor that targets transforming acidic coiled-coil-containing protein 3 (TACC3), with potential antineoplastic activity. Upon oral administration, TACC3 PPI inhibitor AO-252 targets and inhibits the interactions of TACC3 with its protein partners, including clathrin/KIFC1, BARD1 and MBD2/HAT complexes. This may inhibit tumor cell growth. TACC3 plays an important role in the regulation of mitosis, DNA damage response and epigenetic functions via its interaction with its protein partners.
Astrocytoma, IDH-mutant that is not amenable to surgical resection.

The high mobility group N (HMGN) proteins are a family of nuclear proteins that binds to nucleosomes, changes the architecture of chromatin, and enhances transcription and replication from chromatin templates. They typically contain an NBD (Nucleosome Binding Domain) motif, which anchors these HMG proteins to the nucleosome cores to facilitate HMG-14/-17-dependent changes in higher order chromatin structure.  The intracellular organization of the HMGN (previously known as HMG-14/17) proteins is dynamic and is related to both cell-cycle and transcriptional events. These proteins roam the nucleus, perhaps as part of multiprotein complexes, and their target interactions are modulated by posttranslational modifications. Functional studies on HMGN proteins provide insights into the molecular mechanisms by which structural proteins affect DNA-dependent activities in the context of chromatin. (Trends Biochem Sci 2001 Jul;26(7):431-7)

Private medical care coverage that provides all of Part A (Hospital Insurance) and Part B (Medical Insurance) coverage. Medicare pays a fixed amount every month to the companies offering Medicare Advantage Plans.
A type of Medicare managed health plan designed to meet the unique needs of people with one or more chronic conditions, including diabetes, end-stage renal disease, lung conditions, or heart disease.

A type of Medicare managed health plan for eligible individuals who, for 90 days or longer, have had or are expected to need the level of services provided in a long-term care (LTC) skilled nursing facility (SNF), a LTC nursing facility (NF), a SNF/NF, an intermediate care facility for individuals with intellectual disabilities (ICF/IDD), or an inpatient psychiatric facility.
A type of managed health care that encourages enrollees to use providers from within their network, but allows them to see providers outside of the network for higher out-of-pocket charges.

label.value: Health Maintenance Organization Point of Service

value.value: A type of health maintenance organization (HMO) plan that allows enrollees to get certain services from out-of-network providers, usually at a higher cost for these services than from an in-network provider.
High mobility group protein B1 (215 aa, ~25 kDa) is encoded by the human HMGB1 gene. This protein is involved in the regulation of both chromatin structure and DNA topology.
A type of Medicare Advantage plan not elsewhere listed or described.
Participation in Medicare without enrollment in a managed care plan.
An astrocytic tumor that is not amenable to surgical resection.
A pilocytic astrocytoma that is not amenable to surgical resection.
An oligodendroglioma that is not amenable to surgical resection.
The reemergence of a diffuse glioma after a period of remission.
A diffuse glioma that is not amenable to surgical resection.
A voluntary outpatient prescription drug benefit for people with Medicare. Medicare drug plans are provided through private plans that contract with the federal government.

A type of Medicare Advantage plan that combines a high-deductible health plan with a medical savings account. Enrollees are able to put pre-tax earnings into a savings account and use these funds to pay out-of-pocket medical costs until they meet their deductible.
A type of Medicare non-managed plan not elsewhere listed or described.
High mobility group protein B3 (200 aa, ~23 kDa) is encoded by the human HMGB3 gene. This protein is involved in DNA morphology.
Medical coverage through Medicare Part A or Medicare Advantage that pays for hospice services.

Medical coverage for individuals who are eligible for both Medicare and Medicaid. Medicare is their primary source of health insurance coverage, and Medicaid, jointly funded by federal and state governments, provides supplemental coverage.
A managed care plan for individuals who qualify for both Medicare and Medicaid and who qualify for a special needs program.

label.value: Fully Integrated Dual Eligible Special Needs Plan

value.value: A managed care plan that fully integrates care under a single managed care organization for individuals who qualify for both Medicare and Medicaid and who qualify for a special needs program.
A Medicare coverage plan not elsewhere listed or described.

Third party companies that function as intermediaries between insurance providers and pharmaceutical manufacturers. They create formularies, negotiate rebates with manufacturers, process claims, create pharmacy networks, review drug utilization, and sometimes manage mail-order specialty pharmacies.
Managed care plans that provide Medicaid health benefits and additional services through contracted arrangements between state Medicaid agencies and managed care organizations.
A system of managed care used by state Medicaid agencies where a primary care provider is responsible for approving and monitoring the care of enrolled Medicaid beneficiaries.
Medicaid plans or services not elsewhere listed or described.
A Medicaid managed care plan not elsewhere listed or described.
A protein tyrosine kinase inhibitor that competitively inhibits epidermal growth factor receptor kinase activity. (NCI)
High mobility group protein B2 (209 aa, ~24 kDa) is encoded by the human HMGB2 gene. This protein plays a role in DNA unwinding.
Medicaid medical coverage that is not acquired through a managed care system or plan.

label.value: Medicaid State-sponsored Children's Health Insurance Program

value.value: A health insurance program that provides health coverage to eligible children, through both Medicaid and separate Children's Health Insurance programs (CHIP). CHIP is administered by states, according to federal requirements. The program is funded jointly by states and the federal government.
The reemergence of glioneuronal and neuronal tumors after a period of remission.
An exception to Medicaid's rules that do not cover the cost of services for care outside of a beneficiary's home state except for life-threatening emergencies.

label.value: Medicaid Long Term Services and Supports

value.value: Medicaid services for individuals over 65, individuals with physical disabilities, individuals with intellectual disabilities, and chronically ill children. It is available to these participants based on medical necessity and technical and financial eligibility, and covers care in home, community-based settings, and in institutions.

Dental service coverage paid through Medicaid. It is made available to all enrolled children through the Children's Health Insurance Program (CHIP), but states choose whether to provide dental benefits for adults.
Government programs for health care coverage not elsewhere listed or described.
